Here is what was implemented.

### Cause
`ApplyMCPPortPatch` unmarshalled the whole frontmatter into `map[string]interface{}` and wrote it back with `yaml.Encoder`, so the library **re-sorted keys and normalised style** for the entire document.

### Fix
[`ApplyMCPPortPatch`](internal/ghawfrontmatter/ghawfrontmatter.go) now unmarshals into a **`yaml.Node`** tree, only creates/updates **`features` → `mcp-gateway`** and **`sandbox` → `mcp` → `port`**, then encodes the same document node with indent 2. Helpers: `findMapValueNode`, `getOrCreateMapping`, `setScalarKey`.

```211:275:internal/ghawfrontmatter/ghawfrontmatter.go
// ApplyMCPPortPatch rewrites the YAML frontmatter to set features.mcp-gateway: true
// and sandbox.mcp.port. The markdown body after the closing --- is preserved.
// It updates the YAML AST in place so unrelated keys keep order and style.
func ApplyMCPPortPatch(data []byte, port int) ([]byte, error) {
	// ...
	var doc yaml.Node
	if err := yaml.Unmarshal(yamlDoc, &doc); err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	// ...
	features, err := getOrCreateMapping(top, "features")
	// ...
	setScalarKey(features, "mcp-gateway", &yaml.Node{
		Kind:  yaml.ScalarNode,
		Tag:   "!!bool",
		Value: "true",
	})
	sandbox, err := getOrCreateMapping(top, "sandbox")
	// ...
	mcp, err := getOrCreateMapping(sandbox, "mcp")
	// ...
	setScalarKey(mcp, "port", &yaml.Node{
		Kind:  yaml.ScalarNode,
		Tag:   "!!int",
		Value: strconv.Itoa(port),
	})
	// Encode(&doc) ...
}
```

### Errors
If `features`, `sandbox`, or `sandbox.mcp` exists but is **not** a mapping, you get a clear error (e.g. `features: "features" is not a mapping (kind ...)`).

### Tests
In [`ghawfrontmatter_test.go`](internal/ghawfrontmatter/ghawfrontmatter_test.go): **`TestApplyMCPPortPatch_preservesUnrelatedYAML`** checks `toolsets: [default]`, `title-prefix: "[ci-coach] "`, and the `on` block stay verbatim while `mcp-gateway` and `port` are updated; three tests cover bad `features` / `sandbox` / `mcp` types.

`go test ./...` passes. All related todos are marked completed.

